<li id="cite_note-114"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-114">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">In <i><a href="/wiki/Major_Trends_in_Jewish_Mysticism" title="Major Trends in Jewish Mysticism">Major Trends in Jewish Mysticism</a></i> 1941, Gershom Scholem took a historical view of popular Jewish imagination, interacting with national traumas to internalise and develop new Kabbalistic theologies</span>
